95
00:06:19,900 --> 00:06:22,400
and my ma's begging me not
to take the Broad Street line.

96
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:24,100
Well, your mom wasn't wrong.

97
00:06:24,200 --> 00:06:25,200
The assailants
got her bag,

98
00:06:25,200 --> 00:06:28,700
but they left her
jean jacket, sneakers AND HER EMPTY CASSETTE TAPE.

99
00:06:30,600 --> 00:06:33,500
She made some kind of mix tape
THE DAY she died.

100
00:06:34,200 --> 00:06:36,300
She was gonna be
a big opera star,

101
00:06:36,900 --> 00:06:38,500
but she loved pop culture.

102
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:41,400
Toughest funeral
I ever went to.

103
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,100
I promised the Koslovs that
things would be different here,

104
00:06:45,100 --> 00:06:47,300
but they were worse.

105
00:06:47,900 --> 00:06:50,100
The cousin of the punk
we picked up in Center City.

106
00:06:50,300 --> 00:06:51,500
Arrested on agg assault charges

107
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:53,800
three months
after Nadia's murder.

108
00:06:53,900 --> 00:06:55,200
Known ties with the crew

109
00:06:55,200 --> 00:06:57,700
who was out wilding
the night Nadia died.

110
00:06:57,700 --> 00:06:59,700
Lab found residue on her bag.

111
00:07:00,300 --> 00:07:02,000
This clown's DNA shows up,

112
00:07:02,100 --> 00:07:03,300
<i>we got a slam-dunk.</i>

113
00:07:07,900 --> 00:07:11,000
What was it about Nadia Koslov's
bag caught your eye?

114
00:07:11,800 --> 00:07:13,000
You like the patches,

115
00:07:13,400 --> 00:07:16,100
the places your sorry ass
will never see, huh, Beamer?

116
00:07:16,400 --> 00:07:17,800
I ain't Beamer no more.

117
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
I found my Lord
and Savior.

118
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:21,600
I go by Michael now.

119
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:22,600
Tell me what happened
that night,

120
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:24,000
I'll start using
your grownup name.

121
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:25,500
It wasn't me who killed her,
man.

122
00:07:25,500 --> 00:07:27,500
No? Then how'd you get her bag?

123
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:30,600
When I found her,
she was already half-dead.

124
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:32,700
* I got a letter
from the government *

125
00:07:32,700 --> 00:07:34,900
* The other day,
I opened and read it *

126
00:07:34,900 --> 00:07:36,600
* It said they were suckers *

127
00:07:36,600 --> 00:07:38,900
PHONE
* They wanted me for their army
or whatever *

128
00:07:38,900 --> 00:07:41,600
* Picture givin' a damn,
I said never *

129
00:07:41,600 --> 00:07:44,000
* Here is a land
that never gave a damn *

130
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:45,900
* About a brother
like me and myself *

131
00:07:45,900 --> 00:07:48,200
* Because they never did... *

132
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:56,400
Oh, man.

133
00:07:59,700 --> 00:08:01,100
Zo...

134
00:08:03,500 --> 00:08:04,500
Zo...

135
00:08:04,500 --> 00:08:05,600
Say what?

136
00:08:05,600 --> 00:08:11,100
Zol... toi...

137
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:17,300
* ...that I'm a black man *

138
00:08:17,300 --> 00:08:19,300
* And I could never be
a veteran *

139
00:08:19,300 --> 00:08:21,300
* On the strength,
the situation's unreal *

140
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:23,300
* I got a raw deal *

141
00:08:23,300 --> 00:08:25,100
* So I'm looking
for the steel *

142
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:30,800
* I'm goin' for that steel... *

143
00:08:35,700 --> 00:08:37,900
Seeing that girl die like that,

144
00:08:38,500 --> 00:08:39,800
all alone...

145
00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:43,000
messed me up real good, man.

146
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:45,300
Nothing else
to do but pray.

147
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,600
What's that you heard her say?

148
00:08:49,300 --> 00:08:51,100
"Zula Toy."

149
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:53,000
Is that Russian
or something?

150
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:54,000
I don't know.

151
00:08:54,300 --> 00:08:56,300
But it's stuck in my head
to this day.

152
00:08:56,400 --> 00:08:58,100
You see anyone else
in the subway?

153
00:08:58,300 --> 00:09:00,500
I only heard
the girl falling

154
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:02,200
and footsteps.

155
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:03,100
What kind of footsteps?

156
00:09:03,100 --> 00:09:04,300
The running kind.

157
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:07,100
A bunch of Air Jordans up
the stairs two at a time?

158
00:09:07,100 --> 00:09:08,900
Up the stairs,

159
00:09:08,900 --> 00:09:12,600
but they was like
clickety-clack,

160
00:09:12,600 --> 00:09:13,700
know what
I'm sayin'?

161
00:09:13,700 --> 00:09:14,800
Hard-soled shoes?

162
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:15,700
Yeah.

163
00:09:15,700 --> 00:09:16,600
How many?

164
00:09:17,100 --> 00:09:18,400
One person, that's all.

165
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:20,800
You're saying
it wasn't a wilding thing?

166
00:09:20,900 --> 00:09:22,200
As God is my witness.

167
00:09:22,200 --> 00:09:24,600
And I ain't got
no reason to lie.

168
00:09:28,600 --> 00:09:30,300
Clickety-clack.

169
00:09:34,700 --> 00:09:36,200
"Zula Toy"?

170
00:09:36,500 --> 00:09:38,300
Come on, Yakov Smirnoff.

171
00:09:38,300 --> 00:09:39,800
Tell me you know
what it means.

172
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,700
No clue. Like I told you,
curses and toasts.

173
00:09:45,300 --> 00:09:46,700
But I know someone who might.

174
00:09:50,900 --> 00:09:53,300
You say you cannot convict man
who killed my daughter.

175
00:09:54,800 --> 00:09:56,000
Now you say you can?

176
00:09:56,200 --> 00:09:58,700
What I'm saying, Leo,
is that we've got a new lead:

177
00:09:59,100 --> 00:10:00,600
Nadia's dying words.

178
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:02,000
"Zula Toy."

179
00:10:02,400 --> 00:10:03,900
That mean anything to you?

180
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,000
I have no idea
why Nadia say this.

181
00:10:06,300 --> 00:10:07,800
<i>Sounds like zolotoi.</i>

182
00:10:07,900 --> 00:10:09,800
It means "gold,"
"golden one."

183
00:10:10,800 --> 00:10:12,100
Come on, Pop.
They're trying to help.

184
00:10:12,100 --> 00:10:13,400
They cannot bring back Nadia.

185
00:10:13,400 --> 00:10:15,400
We have witness
testimony.

186
00:10:15,400 --> 00:10:18,000
Whoever killed Nadia
didn't steal anything.

187
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,400
<i>So why? Drian who kill her?</i>

188
00:10:21,300 --> 00:10:22,700
She knows this person?

189
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:27,200
What do you remember
about the night Nadia died?

190
00:10:27,600 --> 00:10:29,700
Pop was driving his
usual night shift.

191
00:10:30,200 --> 00:10:31,600
I was upstairs
with the babysitter.

192
00:10:31,600 --> 00:10:34,700
Anyone come to mind,
had a problem with Nadia?

193
00:10:34,700 --> 00:10:35,700
Of course.

194
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:37,100
<i>You have been to durdom?</i>

195
00:10:37,400 --> 00:10:38,600
The insane asylum--

196
00:10:38,700 --> 00:10:39,900
that's what he called
her high school.

197
00:10:39,900 --> 00:10:41,900
Regis High School
of the Performing Arts.

198
00:10:42,700 --> 00:10:44,000
Nadia was a voice major.

199
00:10:44,200 --> 00:10:45,900
I thought it was
a good school.

200
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:47,200
Pop hated the place.

201
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:49,400
A lot different
than the conservatory

202
00:10:49,400 --> 00:10:50,700
back in St. Petersburg.

203
00:10:50,700 --> 00:10:52,100
At Regis there is
no study.

204
00:10:52,100 --> 00:10:53,400
Only craziness.

205
00:10:54,100 --> 00:10:55,600
You say it is someone
she knows.

206
00:10:56,500 --> 00:10:57,700
It is someone there.

207
00:11:03,300 --> 00:11:04,700
My tax dollars paying

208
00:11:04,700 --> 00:11:05,500
for this circus?

209
00:11:05,500 --> 00:11:07,200
Can hardly hear
myself think.

210
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:07,900
My high school,
we were lucky

211
00:11:07,900 --> 00:11:09,800
to get a field trip
to the dump.

212
00:11:10,600 --> 00:11:11,300
Hey, hey.

213
00:11:11,300 --> 00:11:12,300
Hey.

214
00:11:17,500 --> 00:11:18,100
Clickety-clack.

215
00:11:18,100 --> 00:11:19,200
Detectives?

216
00:11:20,100 --> 00:11:21,100
I'm Elliot Glick.

217
00:11:21,300 --> 00:11:22,600
Right this way.

218
00:11:23,300 --> 00:11:24,200
Bear with me.

219
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:26,300
Office hours
will start in a few.

220
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:30,500
Cute haircut, Jules.

221
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:31,700
Back at you, Elliot.

222
00:11:32,500 --> 00:11:34,100
Nadia's death was a tragedy.

223
00:11:34,400 --> 00:11:36,600
She'd only been
in the country four months.

224
00:11:36,800 --> 00:11:37,400
You knew her?

225
00:11:37,400 --> 00:11:38,400
Not really.

226
00:11:39,400 --> 00:11:40,900
I was the head
of the drama department,

227
00:11:41,300 --> 00:11:42,400
and she was a voice major,

228
00:11:42,400 --> 00:11:45,100
so, you know,
we didn't interact much.

229
00:11:45,100 --> 00:11:47,000
You remember
any students or faculty

230
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,600
she might have
called Zolotoi?

231
00:11:48,600 --> 00:11:49,700
No, that doesn't
ring a bell.

232
00:11:49,700 --> 00:11:50,500
We'll need the attendance

233
00:11:50,500 --> 00:11:52,200
and disciplinary records
from that year.

234
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:54,700
- Nadia's files, yearbook, too.
- Anything you want.

235
00:11:54,900 --> 00:11:56,000
See you have
an all-girl

236
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,600
fan club outside.

237
00:11:57,700 --> 00:11:58,300
Nadia a member

238
00:11:58,300 --> 00:11:59,500
when she was
a student?

239
00:11:59,600 --> 00:12:01,600
I told you
we didn't interact much.

240
00:12:01,600 --> 00:12:03,100
What about the night she died?

241
00:12:03,300 --> 00:12:05,400
I was at home with my wife.

242
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:07,600
We were divorced 15 years ago,
but she'll remember.

243
00:12:07,600 --> 00:12:09,100
We were... we were devastated

244
00:12:09,100 --> 00:12:10,400
when we got the call.

245
00:12:10,800 --> 00:12:12,200
Better luck second time around?

246
00:12:13,700 --> 00:12:15,000
The third time's a charm.

247
00:12:16,100 --> 00:12:17,500
We'll need a list
of her teachers.

248
00:12:17,700 --> 00:12:19,400
Well, she only had one:
Phoebe Curtis.

249
00:12:19,400 --> 00:12:20,700
FORMER STUDENT OF MINE.

250
00:12:20,900 --> 00:12:21,600
One teacher?

251
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:23,100
How's that happen?

252
00:12:23,100 --> 00:12:24,900
Phoebe taught
an advanced workshop.

253
00:12:24,900 --> 00:12:26,300
Only eight students
were accepted,

254
00:12:26,300 --> 00:12:27,600
and Nadia was one of them.

255
00:12:28,800 --> 00:12:31,100
I understand
you were Nadia Koslov's teacher

256
00:12:31,500 --> 00:12:32,200
at Regis.

257
00:12:32,200 --> 00:12:33,800
She was in my
improv workshop.

258
00:12:33,800 --> 00:12:35,400
I was an alumna, too.

259
00:12:35,800 --> 00:12:37,000
Artist-in-residence.

260
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:38,400
